    {
      "id": "6685663bb2fffb33a29caf313b6b92a85261a782",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2011-09-07 19:17:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)\n\nSo I don't see anything against this patch in principle, but I am a bit at loss how a file opened for write would cause the llog to be truncated on restart.\nCan you explain a bit please?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "3a478acd0a3a060e1561f69632245f3b30a90499",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-09-20 22:13:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(6 inline comments)\n\nThe commit summary for this patch implies that opening the llog read-only will avoid corruption of the llog file, but I don't think that is an accurate description of the problem being hit, nor is it describing what this patch is actually fixing.\n\nIf I would guess from reading the patch, it seems that it is using the LLOG_CREATE_RO flag avoiding the creation of a new llog file, when the original one was not successfully written?\n\nI think it would be a lot more understandable if this method was renamed to llog_*open() instead of llog_*create().  The LLOG_CREATE_RO flag name doesn't really mean anything sensible.  It might be better to have open flags like LLOG_OPEN_RO = 0, LLOG_OPEN_CREATE = 1, and LLOG_OPEN_RW = 2 (it doesn't make sense to use LLOG_OPEN_RO with the other two flags).\n\nAlso, having a test case that demonstrates this problem would be excellent, so we know it remains fixed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "b37fc4d943eea9091fccc02bec706399db6487cb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 118,
        "name": "Mikhail Pershin",
        "email": "mpershin@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "tappro"
      },
      "date": "2012-11-29 04:41:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nDoes it still make sense? It will not apply to the current master because of llog over OSD changes. If problem still exists please update patch according with all reviews or just abandon it",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
